ce:section.ce:para:
The reusability of the N@CDs prepared from BSA is important for recycling the culture medium. To determine this, reusability studies were performed by using the same used N@CDs for treating fresh H. pluvialis cultures. The photostability of N@CDs was tested by measuring the emission spectra of the N@CDs-culture mix with excitation wavelength of 390nm at day 0 and after 7days of incubation under the same high light intensity (450μmolphotonsm−2
                        s−1). After the addition of N@CDs (diluted 10 x) to H. pluvialis culture, the blue fluorescence of N@CDs was substantially quenched, indicating for the blue light absorbance during the algal cell excitation process, and the high biocompatibility between the cells and the nanoparticles. This measurement was continued for 3 more weeks. No significant changes on the quality of fluorescence of N@CDs were detected after this period (Fig. 4
                        ). Moreover, the QY of N@CDs was similar before and after use (~44%). This result also confirms that the N@CDs are not taken up by the algal cells, and thus can be recycled. These N@CDs could be used four times (1month) without any treatment, which did not aggregate during the examination time (Fig. S1). In a comparative study using carbon dots directly into the algal culture, a recent report by Kim et al. (2016) [2] shows that adding magnesium amino clay nanoparticles directly to Chlorella sp. KR-1 culture could increase lipid productivity of this alga. However; the results showed toxicity effects of the particles on the living cells, and thus the growth was inhibited.
